A crucial step in any siRNA transfection experiment is to assess the level of knockdown of expression induced by such treatment. The section below describes how to evaluate siRNA knockdown by measuring the lowering of ezrin protein expression using a Western blot approach (see
Note
11).Lyse cells by adding 100 μl lysis buffer per well (see
Note
12), and incubate plate at room temperature for 15 min. Perform gentle up down pipetting to ensure lysis is complete.Add 40 μl 4× Loading buffer, 16 μl 10 × DTT, and 4 μl H2O to each sample.Boil samples at 95 °C for 5 min.Cool samples down on ice and perform a quick centrifugation to bring down condensate. At this point, samples can be run through a gel or stored at −20 °C for later analysis.Place the pre-cast Bis-Tris polyacrylamide gel in electrophoresis module (see
Note
13).Fill inner and outer compartments of electrophoresis module with the 1× running buffer.Load 10 μl of molecular weight standard ladder and load 10 μl of samples in each lane.Run electrophoresis using following settings: 200 V with constant voltage for 45–60 min.Cut out Whatman paper and PVDF membrane to the gel dimensions.Dehydrate PVDF membrane in 100 % ethanol for 1 min.Rehydrate membrane in H2O for 5 min, and then incubate it in 1× transfer buffer for 5 min.Soak blotting paper and sponge pads in 1× transfer buffer for at least 5 min.Remove gel from plastic encasing and immerse gel in 1× transfer buffer.Prepare transfer stack by layering (from bottom to top) two blotting sponge pads, three blotting paper cutouts, gel, PVDF membrane. Gently roll out bubbles with roller, e.g., a small pipette. Continue stack by adding three blotting paper cutouts and two sponge pads.Place the stack in transfer module and perform transfer inside electrophoresis module filled with 1× transfer buffer using the following settings: 170 mA constant current for 1–2 h.Remove membrane from stack and place in TBST solution.Block membrane in blocking solution for 1 h at room temperature.Prepare primary antibody solutions by diluting them in blocking solution: rabbit polyclonal anti-ezrin: 1/1,000; goat anti-GAPDH 1/10,000.Cut a straight line on the membrane at 50 kDa marker. Incubate top part with anti-ezrin antibody solution and the bottom part with anti-GAPDH antibody solution for 1 h each.Wash membranes three times 10 min in TBST.Prepare secondary antibodies by diluting them in blocking solution: HRP goat anti-rabbit IgG 1/1,000; HRP rabbit anti-goat IgG 1/1,000.Incubate membranes in the corresponding secondary antibody solutions for 45 min.Wash membranes three times 10 min in TBST.Mix ECL solutions using a 1:1 ratio and add 1–2 mL of mixed solution to membrane surface.Incubate for 1 min, remove excess moisture, and perform band detection using gel doc or film and developer (Fig. 2).
Perform band quantification analysis using Gel Analysis module of ImageJ or similar software. For each lane, the GAPDH (housekeeping protein) band serves as a loading control. Normalize ezrin band relative intensity (I
ezrin) to GAPDH band relative intensity (I
GAPDH):
